 on women’s roles, relationships, and identities. Analyzing women as subjects and agents, the book examines how they negotiated the challenges that arose as Romanian society modernized, even as it clung to traditional ideas about gender. Massino concludes by exploring the ambiguities of postsocialism, highlighting how the legacies of the past have shaped politics and women’s lived experiences since 1989.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGender identityzRomania. 0aWomen and communismzRomaniaxHistory. 0aWomenzRomaniaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311099772940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785335990?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785335990423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785335990/original  a978-3-11-099772-9  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK